128. Longest Consecutive Sequence

Intuition

We need the longest sequence of consecutive numbers.

Example:

[100,4,200,1,3,2]

The consecutive sequence is:

1,2,3,4

Length = 4

Brute Force Idea

For every number:

check if num + 1 exists
then num + 2
then num + 3

But searching every time takes:

O(N²)

Not allowed.

The problem specifically asks for:

O(N)
Optimal Idea — Use HashSet

A HashSet gives:

O(1)

average lookup time.

So:

Put all elements into a set
Start sequence only if current number is the START
Expand forward
Most Important Observation

Suppose:

1,2,3,4

If we start from every element:

from 1 → length 4
from 2 → length 3
from 3 → length 2

This causes repeated work.

So we ONLY start when:

num - 1 does NOT exist

Meaning:

current number is the beginning of a sequence
